 [[us003|rotate service credentials without downtime]]
 
 ## approach
-Adopt the vault-rotate-policy pattern via [[ft002]]: writers stage the
-new credential under a versioned alias; readers fall back to the prior
-version for up to 5 minutes; alias flips at the end of the window.
+Vault writes are staged under a per-name versioned alias list; readers
+return the latest version via `secret(name)`. The rotation primitive
+appends a new version under a per-name `threading.Lock` so concurrent
+rotations for the same name serialize while different names progress
+independently. The orchestration layer ([[ft002]] + `vault_rotate.py`)
+holds the 5-minute overlap timer; the alias bookkeeping itself is
+contained in `vault.py`.
 
 ## features
 - [[ft002|vault-secrets]]
 
 ## data_model
-No schema change. Vault holds versioned aliases.
+In-process per-name alias list (`_ALIASES: dict[str, list[str]]`) plus a
+per-name lock registry (`_LOCKS: dict[str, threading.Lock]`) guarded by a
+single `_LOCKS_GUARD` lock. No schema change in Vault — versioned aliases
+are how the backend already represents history.
 
 ## api_surface
-`acme.lib.vault.secret(name)` continues to be the only read path; writes
-use a new internal `rotate_secret(name)` helper that lands in the same lib.
+- `acme.lib.vault.secret(name) -> str` — read path, returns the latest
+  staged version (or `<vault:{name}>` if none).
+- `acme.lib.vault.rotate_secret(name, new_value) -> None` — write path.
+  Per-name serialization; raises `ValueError` on empty name/value,
+  wraps backend errors as `VaultError`.
+- `acme.lib.vault.VaultError` — exception type for backend rejection.
 
 ## components
 - `src/lib/vault.py`
